    <stitle>International&#174; T 444E Diesel Engine Service, Model Year 1994 - 1998 - ENGINE ELECTRICAL</stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcsection id="Section10" svcsectype="enginesec" division="engine" date="2-21-02">
        <title>ENGINE ELECTRICAL</title>
        <description>
            <geninfo>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Refer to the following for electrical system troubleshooting.</para>
                        <para>EGES-125-1, Diagnostic Manual</para>
                        <para>EGED-130-1, Performance Analysis Guide</para>
                        <para>EGED-135-1, Electronics Diagnostic Form</para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </geninfo>
            <geninfo>
                <title>Camshaft Position (CMP) Sensor</title>
                <figure id="f1201009" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../figeg3/EG3371.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="328px"
                             scalefitheight="472px" box="yes"/>
                    <caption>Camshaft Position Sensor Location</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">Camshaft Position (CMP) Sensor</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
                <para>The CMP sensor is a Hall effect type sensor that is used to indicate the engine speed and camshaft
                    position. This sensor is located above the vibration damper on the right side of the engine front
                    cover.
                </para>
            </geninfo>
            <geninfo>
                <title>Exhaust Back Pressure (EBP) Sensor</title>
                <figure id="f1201010" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../figeg3/EG3370.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="yes"/>
                    <caption>EBP and ECT Sensor Locations</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">Exhaust Back Pressure (EBP) Sensor</callout1>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">Engine Coolant Temperature (ECT) Sensor</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
                <para>A ceramic diaphragm sensor is used to measure the exhaust back pressure. The sensor is mounted on
                    a bracket located on the top right side of the hydraulic reservoir. This sensor provides feedback to
                    the ECM for closed loop control of the exhaust back pressure. The result is faster engine warm-up at
                    cold ambient temperatures.
                </para>
                <para>See the engine diagnostic manual for further information.</para>
            </geninfo>
            <geninfo>
                <title>Engine Coolant Temperature (ECT) Sensor</title>
                <para>The ECT is a thermistor type sensor that detects changes in engine coolant temperature. It is
                    located on the right side of the engine front cover, above the water pump.
                </para>
            </geninfo>
            <geninfo>
                <title>Engine Oil Temperature (EOT) Sensor</title>
                <figure id="f1201011" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../figeg3/EG3367.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="yes"/>
                    <caption>EOT and ICP Sensor Locations</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">Injection Control Pressure (ICP) Sensor</callout1>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">Engine Oil Temperature (EOT) Sensor</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
                <para>The EOT is a thermistor type sensor that detects the engine oil temperature. It is located on back
                    left side of the high pressure oil reservoir. This sensor is provides the engine temperature signal
                    to the ECM. The ECM uses the information for fuel rate and timing adjustments.
                </para>
            </geninfo>
            <geninfo>
                <title>Injection Control Pressure (ICP) Sensor</title>
                <para>The ICP is a ceramic diaphragm sensor that measures the injection control pressure. It is located
                    toward the front of the engine on the left cylinder head, in the high pressure oil rail. The ICP
                    sensor provides gallery pressure feedback to the ECM for a closed loop control of the injector oil
                    pressure.
                </para>
            </geninfo>
            <geninfo>
                <title>Injection Pressure Regulator (IPR) Valve</title>
                <figure id="f1201012" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../figeg3/EG3369.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                             scalefitheight="472px" box="yes"/>
                    <caption>Injection Pressure Regulator (IPR) Valve Location</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">Injection Pressure Regulator (IPR) Valve</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
                <para>The IPR valve regulates injection control pressure. It is located on the left side of the high
                    pressure pump. The IPR valve is a pulse width modulated valve that controls the injector oil
                    pressure by a signal from the ECM.
                </para>
                <para>See the engine diagnostic manual for further information.</para>
            </geninfo>
        </description>
